2026-03-23 - Frontier Checklist
===============================

Control choices

- Primary trunk: PR #512
- TTT scheduler patch source: PR #517
- Recurrence challenger: PR #499
- DeltaNet: not found in our logs, notes, or fetched frontier branches; treat as a later feasibility spike, not the first branch


Checklist

1. Extract the frontier scripts into local working files.
   Get: one current-best control and one clean TTT-variant source to diff against.

2. Use PR #512 as the default control, not our old local fork.
   Get: all future improvements measured against the actual frontier.

3. Diff PR #512 vs PR #517 only around TTT, not around the whole repo.
   Get: the exact scheduler and adaptation-policy changes worth porting.

4. Make the PR #512 control run cleanly on L40S with single GPU, SDPA, and compile toggle.
   Get: a stable local research harness.

5. Train one checkpoint with the control script and save it.
   Get: a frozen trunk for cheap repeated TTT experiments.

6. Wire the honest scoring path:
   train -> export -> reload exported model -> run eval stack -> score BPB.
   Get: trustworthy selection metrics.

7. Implement the LoRA TTT eval loop on the exported model.
   Get: the fast research loop where one training run supports many eval-time variants.

8. Sweep TTT rank.
   Get: whether adaptation capacity is bottlenecked.

9. Sweep TTT target modules:
   Q+V, Q+V+LM head, broader linear sets.
   Get: where adaptation actually matters.

10. Sweep TTT epochs and schedule.
    Get: whether cosine decay, constant LR, or shorter adaptation wins on our harness.

11. Sweep chunk size, trailing context, and minimum document threshold.
    Get: the best granularity for document-level adaptation.

12. Add doc-isolated eval if it is not already present in the chosen control.
    Get: cleaner evaluation and less contamination across document boundaries.

13. Add Stride-OGD on top of the best TTT setting.
    Get: whether cheap vocab-bias adaptation stacks with TTT.

14. Integrate cross-window KV reuse into sliding eval.
    Get: lower eval cost and more eval budget to spend on adaptation.

15. Add neural cache on top of the best TTT setting.
    Get: whether parametric and non-parametric memory stack.

16. If neural cache is too slow, spike PPM-C or a simpler n-gram mixer.
    Get: a local-memory sidecar even if neural cache is not practical.

17. Keep the winning TTT + eval stack fixed and only then test architecture challengers.
    Get: a fair comparison where trunk families are evaluated on the same frontier eval stack.

18. Port PR #499 recurrence as the first real architecture challenger.
    Get: direct evidence on recurrence + frontier eval stack, not recurrence in isolation.

19. Compare recurrence against the PR #512 control with the same exported-model eval path.
    Get: whether recurrence actually improves final judged BPB once adaptation is included.

20. Keep DeltaNet as a bounded spike:
    implement only if the control loop is already running.
    Get: a yes/no answer on viability without derailing the mainline.

    Key context: DeltaNet IS TTT. Formally proven — delta rule = one step of
    gradient descent on MSE loss per token. The recurrent state is a model
    being trained online during the forward pass. This means:
    - A DeltaNet sidecar alongside the transformer trunk gives native TTT
      without separate LoRA adapters or eval-time gradient steps.
    - Gated DeltaNet (ICLR 2025, NVlabs) adds a decay gate for controlled
      forgetting. Qwen3.5 ships 75% GatedDeltaNet + 25% attention.
    - PR #182 tried Titans-style linearized memory sidecar and got 1.1844 BPB
      with TTT — validates the sidecar approach.
    - Nobody in the competition has tried actual DeltaNet.

    Two spike paths (pick one):
    a. Full DeltaNet hybrid (8 DeltaNet + 3 attn layers). High risk, high reward.
    b. DeltaNet sidecar (keep 11L transformer, add small delta-rule memory per
       block). Lower risk — trunk stays proven, sidecar adds adaptive memory.
       This is the principled version of neural cache.

21. If DeltaNet is spiked, judge it on:
    compile stability, step latency, artifact bytes, and exported-model eval score.
    Get: a hard viability call instead of intuition.
    Also measure: does LoRA TTT STILL help on top of DeltaNet's native TTT?
    If DeltaNet already captures most adaptation value, LoRA TTT may be redundant.

22. Run sp4096 only after the best eval stack exists.
    Get: whether tokenizer gains compound with the current best TTT stack.

23. Promote only candidates that improve final judged BPB, not just TTT delta.
    Get: less metric drift and fewer dead-end branches.

24. Keep light diagnostics on every run:
    prequant BPB, postquant BPB, final judged BPB, adaptation uplift, quant gap, bytes, step time.
    Get: enough signal to mutate quickly.

25. Run heavy diagnostics only on promoted candidates:
    block sensitivity, outlier stats, rank-ish probes, deeper export checks.
    Get: richer insight without slowing every loop.

26. Move only the best one or two candidates to 8xH100.
    Get: real-hardware confirmation without wasting compute.

27. Tune hardware-dependent knobs only on 8xH100:
    batch, warmdown, LR schedule, FA3 policy, DDP behavior.
    Get: final submission settings instead of proxy-only wins.


What we are actually testing

- Whether TTT scheduling still has easy headroom beyond PR #512 and PR #517
- Whether TTT stacks with Stride-OGD
- Whether TTT stacks with local non-parametric memory
- Whether recurrence becomes stronger once evaluated with the best current eval stack
- Whether sp4096 compounds with the winning eval path
- Whether DeltaNet is even viable under compile, runtime, and artifact constraints


Rules

- Do not compare against stale local baselines.
- Do not run architecture search before the TTT loop works.
- Do not treat TTT delta as the objective.
- Do not treat MTP as a default.
- Do not let DeltaNet derail the mainline until the control loop is running.
- Do not promote anything that fails on the exported-model scoring path.
